  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">NIHR Global Health Research Group on African Snakebite Research</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1) Snakebite Rapid Diagnostic Test: with our Kenya partners and the Liverpool School of Tropical Medicine (LSTM)&#x2019;s Research Centre for Drugs and Diagnosis, we will develop Africa&#x2019;s first near-patient snakebite diagnostic kit. 2) Generation of Important New Research Data by: a) Conducting clinical pharmacological studies of systemic venom/anti-venom interactions. b) Conducting hospital and community surveys in each country to develop accurate estimates of snakebite burden and socio-economic impact. c) Utilising LSTM&#x2019;s preclinical antivenom testing expertise to develop systems for rapid and costeffective antivenom efficacy testing, initially in Kenya. 3) Capacity-Strengthening Benefits: a) We will pilot and establish region-specific first aid, hospital and rehabilitation guidelines and clinical training. b) We will test, first in Kenya and then in Nigeria and Cameroon, the first Snakebite Emergency Response System - a smartphone app-activation of motorcycle ambulances to speed rural snakebite victims to hospital. This will inexpensively improve local health capacity and snakebite outcomes.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">A UK and low- and middle-income country (LMIC) partnership that aims to establish self-sustaining regional hubs of snakebite expertise to support national and regional authorities design and implement systems to reduce snakebite deaths and disability.</narrative>
  </description>
